Regression Project: Boston House Price Prediction¶

Marks: 60¶

Welcome to the project on regression. We will use the Boston house price dataset for this project.

Objective¶

The problem at hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features affecting the price of the house. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for the unseen data.

Dataset¶

Each record in the database describes a house in Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below:

Attribute Information:

  • CRIM: Per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: Proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: Proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: Nitric Oxide concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: The average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: Proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: Weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: Index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: Full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: Pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of 'MEDV' look like?
  2. What can we infer form the correlation heatmap? Is there correlation between the dependent and independent variables?
  3. What are all the inferences that can be found by doing univariate analysis for different variables?
  4. Do bivariate analysis to visualize the relationship between the features having significant correlations (>= 0.7 or <= -0.7)

Univariate analysis¶

Let's take a look at the distibutions of each one of the variables in the data set in order to explore its composition.

In [ ]:

Observations:

  • The target variable MEDV resembles a normal distibution, although somewhat skewed to the right.

  • CRIM and ZN are highly skewed to the right. This can also be seen in the table used previously, by noticing the difference between their measures of centrality and their maximum value.

  • INDUS, RAD and TAX are multi-modal distributions, meaning that they see a high concentration of observations at two different locations.

In order to better visualize the distribution of the dependent variable, we can apply a logaritmic transformation to ease the skewness.

Multicolinearity¶

Let's now check for multicolinearity in the training set. We can use the Variance Infaltion factor, which basically tells us how much the variance of an estimated regression coefficient increases if your predictors are correlated. A high VIF indicates high multicollinearity.

In [ ]:
vif_data = pd.DataFrame() #Create new empty Df
vif_data["Variable"] = X_train.columns #Assign values
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_train.values, i) for i in range(X_train.shape[1])] #Perform test

print(vif_data)

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

1. Mean residuals equal to zero¶

In [ ]:
residuals = model2.resid 

np.mean(residuals)
Out[ ]:
-2.7379228827620387e-15

The mean of the residuals should be zero for our model. As we can see above, this is satisfied since we get a number really close to zero.

2. No heteroscedasticity¶

This means that the residuals of the model should be spred out evenly, so there is no tendency with respect certain values.

There are several ways to test this, even visually, but is better to use a hypothesis test:

  • Null H: Residuals are homoscedastic (desireable)

  • Alternative H: Residuals are heteroscedastic (undesirable)

Therefore, we want a p-value lower than 0.05.

In [ ]:
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(model2.resid, X_train) ## Test
print('P-value of test: ',test[1])

P-value of test:  0.3019012006766869

As we can see, there is heteroscedasticity.

We should see this graphically as well:

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=model2.fittedvalues, y=model2.resid)
plt.axhline(y=0, color='r', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)  # Add a horizontal line at y=0
plt.title('Residuals vs Fitted Values')
plt.xlabel('Fitted Values')
plt.ylabel('Residuals')
plt.show()

Since the residuals are not constant along a straight line, we conclude heteroscedasticity.

3. Lineality of variables¶

In the previous graph we can observe that the fitted values appear randomly and uniformlt scattered, which demostrates linearity of the variables. If they weren't, the values would create a clear pattern.

4. Normality of error terms¶

The residuals should be normally distributed.

In [ ]:
sns.histplot(model2.resid,kde=True)
Out[ ]:
<Axes: ylabel='Count'>

It appears that they are normally distributed. Lets do a QQ plot to make sure:

In [ ]:
stats.probplot(model2.resid, dist = "norm", plot = pylab)

plt.show()

They no longer appear to be normally distributed.

Let's do a final test called de Jarque-Bera test, where the null hypothesis is that the residuals are not normally distributed. In this case we want the p-value to be over 0.05.

In [ ]:
jb_test_statistic, jb_p_value, _, _ = sm.stats.stattools.jarque_bera(model2.resid)

print(f"Jarque-Bera Test Statistic: {jb_test_statistic:.4f}")
print(f"P-value for Jarque-Bera test: {jb_p_value:.4f}")

# Interpret the results
if jb_p_value < 0.05:
    print("The test suggests that the residuals are not normally distributed.")
else:
    print("The test does not provide strong evidence against the normality of residuals.")

Jarque-Bera Test Statistic: 87.3544
P-value for Jarque-Bera test: 0.0000
The test suggests that the residuals are not normally distributed.

Final Model¶

Let's now get some cross validation to get a final model for prediction and insights.

First, let's define some metric and model performance functions to make the code run a bit smoother, then we will run the model:

In [ ]:
# RMSE
def rmse(predictions, targets):
    return np.sqrt(((targets - predictions) ** 2).mean())


# MAPE
def mape(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)) / targets) * 100


# MAE
def mae(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)))

# Model Performance on test and train data
def model_pref(olsmodel, x_train, x_test):

    # In-sample Prediction
    y_pred_train = olsmodel.predict(x_train)
    y_observed_train = y_train

    # Prediction on test data
    y_pred_test = olsmodel.predict(x_test)
    y_observed_test = y_test

    print(
        pd.DataFrame(
            {
                "Data": ["Train", "Test"],
                "RMSE": [
                    rmse(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    rmse(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
                "MAE": [
                    mae(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    mae(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
                "MAPE": [
                    mape(y_pred_train, y_observed_train),
                    mape(y_pred_test, y_observed_test),
                ],
            }
        )
    )

We can see that the R squared value ranges from 0.497 to 0.961, a long stretch, but provides a better understanding of the capabilities of our model. The same for the Mean Squared Error

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • Criminal rate per capita, Nitic Oxide levels, Distances to employment centers, Pupil-teacher ratio and lower status of population are all variables that are negatively associated with the value of owner-occupied homes.

  • Being in the Chass river sees in average an increase in $119.7 dollars in the value of the homes.

  • More rooms are related to a higher value.

  • Greater accesibility to radial highways is related to a higher value.

Talking about the model:

The model does not check the normality of residual nor the heteroscedastisity assumptions. This could cause reliability of the inferences of the model. To perform a better model it could be wise to perform adecuate transformations that fit the data. A visualtization of the response variable with the rest would be helpful in order to perform those transformations. Nevertheless, it is important to note that the assumptions are hardly applicable to real world data, so we should always espect some sort of deviation from the assumptions.
